<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Auto-Backup rules (MF-09).

  What is being backed up:
    DP_QUANTUM_COIN_WALLET_APP_PREF.xml is the SharedPreferences file that
    holds:
      * The scrypt salt (SECURE_DERIVED_KEY_SALT)
      * The scrypt+AES encrypted main key (SECURE_ENCRYPTED_MAIN_KEY)
      * Per-wallet encrypted blobs (SECURE_WALLET_*) that contain the
        address, public/private key and seed phrase encrypted with the
        main key
      * Non-sensitive app state (current wallet index, network list, etc.)
      * The BACKUP_ENABLED flag itself

  Why this is safe to back up:
    Every sensitive value is encrypted with an AES key that is itself
    encrypted with a scrypt-derived key (N=262144, r=8, p=1, keyLen=32).
    Without the user's wallet password the backup is useless to an
    attacker (including Google's backup storage, device images, or the
    receiving device during restore). The password is never stored on
    disk in a recoverable form.

  Runtime gate:
    WalletBackupAgent.onFullBackup() inspects BACKUP_ENABLED_KEY before
    calling super.onFullBackup(). If the user has not explicitly opted
    in from the app Settings UI, the agent returns without emitting
    any data, so even with android:allowBackup="true" in the manifest
    nothing leaves the device.

  Restore behavior:
    On a new install on a new device, Android replays the backup into
    the same SharedPreferences file. Because the encrypted main key and
    all per-wallet blobs travel together, the user only needs their
    original wallet password to unlock on the new device; no seed
    re-import is required.

  Exclusions:
    Everything else (caches, files/*, external storage, etc.) is
    excluded by omitting it from the <include> whitelist below.
-->
<full-backup-content>
    <include domain="sharedpref" path="DP_QUANTUM_COIN_WALLET_APP_PREF.xml" />
</full-backup-content>
